[start section id="20112"]

#1 Stage III colon cancer
I had a long discussion with the patient and the son in the room regarding the situation.  The patient would be expected to benefit from adjuvant chemotherapy.  The benefit from chemotherapy is likely to amount to an approximately 50% reduction in the chance of death in five years with the risk of recurrence without chemotherapy in the 30% to 40% range and a risk of recurrence after chemotherapy approximately 10% to 20%.
The patient is to recover from the surgery first, which could take four to six-weeks.  He is pretty confident that he would be wanting treatment back home.
I discussed with him that we will have him come back and see Dr. Stubbs for one more visit in a few weeks while he is recovering.
The patient appreciated the consultation.  He will let us know if he decides to go straight home after he heals from the surgery, at which point we can send our records to his home oncologist with our recommendations for six-months of FOLFOX chemotherapy.
He is currently being evaluated by Cardiology for shortness-of-breath he experienced last night.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn.  No apparent learning barriers were identified.  Learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

[end section id="20112"]

