#1 Stage III colon cancer

[end section id="20113"]

[start section id="20102"]

Stage III colon cancer.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

A 60-year-old gentleman from the Inglewood presented with anemia requiring 3 units of blood.  A colonoscopy in April 2010 revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, 120 cm from the anal verge.  A CT-scan showed a right lobe density and a small right pleural effusion, and an MRI showed multiple suspicious small nodules.  On further review, these nodules were hypervascular in nature and likely benign.  Baseline CEA was 7.7.
A PET scan showed disease in the proximal descending colon right below the splenic flexure, and there was no uptake in the liver.
On June 21, the patient underwent a wedge resection of a liver lesion, finding a cavernous hemangioma 1-cm in size, and a left colon resection revealed a 7-cm grade 2 annular mass in the transverse colon invading through the muscularis propria into the pericolic fat (T3) with negative margins.  One out of 27 original lymph nodes were positive for metastasis involving less than 0.01 cm (N1).  Total stage T3, N1, M0, stage IIIB.
Patient had met prior to the operation with Dr. Stubbs.  We were called by the Surgical Team to discuss with the patient adjuvant options.

[end section id="20103"]

